
[1]snow

   SNOW, n. [L. nix,nivis; The Latin nivis, is contracted from nigis, like
   Eng. bow.]

   1. Frozen vapor; watery particles congealed into white crystals in the
   air, and falling to the earth. When there is no wind, these crystals
   fall in flakes or unbroken collections, sometimes extremely beautiful.

   2. A vessel equipped with two masts, resembling the main and fore-masts
   of a ship, and a third small mast just abaft the mainmast, carrying a
   try-sail.

       SNOW, v.i. To fall in snow; as, it snows; it snowed yesterday.

                      SNOW, v.t. To scatter like snow.
